        <body>
            <pb n="1"/>
            <p rend="align(right)"><date>Friday, 18 Sivan (May), 1850</date>, <placeName>New
                    York</placeName></p>
            <p>Peace to the honor of my friend‚Ä¶the author<lb/>‚Ä¶seeker of the welfare of all
                    <placeName>America</placeName>, the<lb/> near and the far. <addressee>Eliezer
                    Lesser</addressee> etc.</p>
            <p>Dear Sir,</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">I come to beg of your Honor to try to<lb/> find for me a
                dwellingîÑ£place where I can<lb/> serve the Holy Cause, to preside over the<lb/>
                sacrifice ([)Prayer(\) and to be a hazan and rabbi. For<lb/> it is my intention to
                move my residence from<lb/> the City of <placeName>Utica</placeName> to whatever
                place I may<lb/> find and which God may send my way.<lb/> I cannot any longer and I
                do not want<lb/> to stay in <placeName>Utica</placeName> because of the
                wickedness<lb/> of its inhabitants. To write down all their<lb/> wicked deeds, how
                evil and sinful they<lb/> are to God and man, would make a<lb/> big book,
                    <del>and</del> for <sic>their</sic> is no measuring nor<lb/> describing it.<lb/>
            </p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">I am sure that are looking to<lb/> appoint for themselves a
                Shohet<lb/> and Hazan, or even a rabbi and<lb/> perhaps a preacher too, if they seek
                the<lb/> truth, will, I trust to God, derive much</p>
            <pb n="2"/>
            <p>joy from a man like me. As to this there<lb/> is the testimony of all the sages of
                    <placeName>Germany</placeName><lb/> and <placeName>Poland</placeName>. Their
                letters are in my bag;<lb/> letters of permission to be shohet, and<lb/> to act as
                rabbi, all announce and testify<lb/> about me that I am fit for that
                <del>job</del><lb/> honor. All the congregation that wants<lb/> to choose me can
                investigate about<lb/> me by inquiring of the rabbi and<lb/> great preacher
                    <persName>Doctor Raphall</persName>, and<lb/> of my friend the pious Mohel
                    <persName>Shneor<lb/> N√ºssbaum</persName>, and of other prominent<lb/> men here.
                But my ways are not known<lb/> to the world in general; nor do wise men<lb/> boast;
                as the wise man said ‚ÄúLet a<lb/> stranger praise thee not thine own mouth‚Äù<lb/>
                Nevertheless, in the case of a man <hi rend="underline">whose<lb/> future seems
                    dark</hi>. <del>be right</del> (or, perhaps,<lb/> the writer meant, ‚Äúwho is very
                modest‚Äù)<lb/> his way will remain dark if he does not<lb/> anyone of his nature and
                doings. He<lb/> should not be despised if he makes him<lb/> self public, to tell
                mankind of his</p>
            <pb n="3"/>
            <p>prowess, and let his friends praise<lb/> him in the gate.<lb/></p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">When I arrived here last night<lb/> and went to the home of
                    <persName>Doctor Raphall</persName><lb/> and asked him whether he knew a
                resting<lb/> place for me. He told me that <placeName>Chicago</placeName><lb/> seeks
                a Shohet and Hazan. That is<lb/> why I lay my urgent plea before you<lb/>
                <del>to forego your pret pride</del> begging your pardon a thousand times and urging
                you write<lb/> to them to choose me rather than the<lb/> others. You know those
                others and<lb/> their kind. If you, honored Sir, are<lb/> willing to do this, please
                write at<lb/> once, by the first post. In return<lb/> you will have peace in this
                world and<lb/> the next because you had mercy on<lb/> a humble soul like me and
                caused<lb/> sighing spirits to rejoice; i.e. my<lb/> wife and son whose eyes
                look<lb/> to me. How can I help them? Where<lb/> is the store‚Äìhouse or the
                wine‚Äìpress?<lb/> I therefore hope in your good nature</p>
            <pb n="4"/>
            <p>place as shohet and Hazan, I shall<lb/> pay to your Honor a portion of my<lb/> salary
                up to twenty dollars</p>
            <p>The last in <del>t<add>?</add></del> small letters<lb/> at bottom</p>
            <p>On very top his address</p>
            <p><persName>P. Rosenthal</persName><lb/>
                <placeName>Utica N. Y.</placeName><lb/> No. 1 Hatel<add>?</add> Av.</p>
        </body>
